{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dcc6851b-0e22-41e1-833a-46eda65bd6da","content":"## What happened\n\n`DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS in .NET 11 because **Apple's native crypto frameworks (Security.framework / CryptoKit) have never supported DSA**. In earlier .NET versions, the runtime used an OpenSSL shim on macOS to provide DSA; .NET 11 removed that fallback as part of the ongoing deprecation of legacy algorithms.\n\n## How to fix it\n\n**Option 1 — BouncyCastle (recommended for verify-only scenarios):**\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\n// Import your existing DSA public key (e.g., from X.509 SubjectPublicKeyInfo)\nAsymmetricKeyParameter pubKey = PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(spkiBytes);\n\nISigner signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA1withDSA\"); // match your legacy hash\nsigner.Init(forSigning: false, pubKey);\nsigner.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);\nbool valid = signer.VerifySignature(signatureBytes);\n```\n\nThis is a pure managed implementation — works identically on Linux, Windows, and macOS with no native dependencies.\n\n**Option 2 — Platform guard + conditional OpenSSL:**\n\nIf you must keep using `System.Security.Cryptography`, guard the call and only use DSA on platforms that support it:\n\n```csharp\nif (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())\n{\n    using var dsa = DSA.Create();\n    // ...\n}\nelse\n{\n    // fall back to BouncyCastle or reject gracefully\n}\n```\n\n**Option 3 — Migrate signatures to ECDSA/EdDSA.** If you control the signing side, re-sign with a modern algorithm. DSA is considered legacy and increasingly unsupported across platforms.\n\n**Recommendation:** Go with BouncyCastle — it gives you a single cross-platform code path and avoids `#if` / runtime branching entirely.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5da904f2-8fe6-4b7f-832f-f4f42aecc24c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me think about what I know about this topic.\n\nThis is a well-known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7 (and continuing forward), .NET began deprecating older cryptographic algorithms. Specifically, regarding DSA on macOS:\n\nIn .NET 7, there was a breaking change where `DSA.Create()` throws a `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS. This is because macOS (via Apple's Security framework / CommonCrypto) never had native support for DSA, and .NET previously used OpenSSL on macOS for DSA support. When .NET moved away from depending on OpenSSL on macOS (preferring Apple's native crypto APIs), DSA support was dropped on that platform.\n\n\nI'm second-guessing the exact version timeline here. The DSA deprecation on macOS actually happened earlier in .NET's lifecycle, and I should be more precise about when Apple's security frameworks stopped supporting it and how that cascaded through different .NET versions. through workarounds like BouncyCastle for signature verification, direct OpenSSL interop, or migrating to newer algorithms if possible. The core issue is that Microsoft has been phasing out DSA support on macOS since it relies on OpenSSL rather than native security frameworks, and this trend likely continues into .NET 10/11. I think the real issue is that .NET 11 removed DSA support on macOS because Apple's native crypto frameworks don't have it, and the OpenSSL fallback that existed in earlier versions is gone. The best solutions are to switch to BouncyCastle for a pure managed implementation or call OpenSSL directly through P/Invoke.","outputTokens":1757,"requestId":"B41B:36154C:8B5334:AD1D62:6A013563"},"id":"865c8282-4a8a-4f25-a653-db0346889881","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:48:58.409Z","parentId":"e696842b-530b-4f46-b1cc-13461a054fc2"}
